            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, her small hand swallowed by her father\u2019s as they stood at the bus stop on International Boulevard. The bus was 20 minutes late. She felt his calm fa\u00e7ade crack, the quiet tension of a man calculating lost wages in his head. The world, for that moment, shrank to the injustice of their wait, the helplessness of relying on a system that didn\u2019t see them. It wasn't a policy problem then; it was the knot in her stomach, a feeling that would fuel her for decades to come.\n\n2.\nIt was 2 AM in the university library during her Goldman internship. A spreadsheet of late-night ridership on the 24-Divisadero line blurred before her eyes. Then, a cluster of data points coalesced into a person: a nurse from SF General, exhausted. The numbers weren\u2019t abstract anymore; they were stories of sacrifice, dictated by service hours. In that silent, fluorescent-lit moment, lucrative consulting gigs dissolved. There was only this\u2014the data that bled humanity, and her overwhelming need to serve it.\n\n3.\nHer first project was minor: analyzing rider feedback to justify adding a bench and shelter at an exposed bus stop in the Bayview. Six months later, riding the T-Third on a Saturday, she saw it. An older man sat on the new bench, shielded from the wind, reading a paper. No one knew her role in its existence. Seeing that small moment of dignity and comfort\u2014a direct result of her work\u2014was more validating than any promotion. It was a physical manifestation of her purpose.\n\n4.\nLast winter, the N-Judah stalled in the tunnel. An elderly woman, clutching grocery bags, became audibly distressed about getting home before dark. Imani, instinctively switching from analyst to neighbor, helped her navigate the bus bridge transfer. The woman\u2019s relieved \u201cGod bless you\u201d wasn\u2019t for an SFMTA employee, but for a kind stranger. For Imani, it was a sharp, humbling reminder that her work wasn\u2019t just about system efficiency, but about delivering someone\u2019s grandmother safely home.\n\n5.\nShe was mapping her equitable fare proposal on their kitchen table, surrounded by her partner\u2019s legal briefs on eviction defense. He traced one of her proposed low-income routes with his finger. \"This line,\" he said, \"is the same one three of my clients use to get to their hearings.\" The sudden, perfect overlay of their worlds\u2014transportation and housing, access and justice\u2014felt like a jolt of electricity. In that instant, her project wasn't just a policy proposal; it was a shield for his clients."
